                <p>
                <td bgcolor="#333366" height="100%" width="100%" colspan="2" valign="top"><a name="100521"></a>
                  <table width="100%" height="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                    <tr>
                      <td colspan="2" valign="top">
                      <img src="images/icon_mi_1.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="" title="" hspace="3" /><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;11/26/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 03:42:25 AM</font>
                      &nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=782"><img src="images/icon_profile.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="Show Profile" title="Show Profile" align="absmiddle" hspace="6" /></a>
                      &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=100521&TOPIC_ID=10917&FORUM_ID=17"><img src="images/icon_reply_topic.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="Reply with Quote" title="Reply with Quote" align="absmiddle" hspace="6" /></a>
                      <hr noshade size="2"></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="Verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Melees are based on equipment, levels, and AAXP.  Casters are based on equipment, levels, AAXP AND spells.  The problem should be obvious.  Why the heck must we have a fourth factor to consider in order to be balanced with melees? It's not like we don't need equipment in order to survive.  The items we receive are in many ways just as important as the items melees receive especially since PoP is so AE-dependent.  This is not the old days where a naked caster was basically 10-20% weaker than a fully armed caster.  We shouldn't be pursuing four different things when melees need only pursue three to be balanced with us.<br /><br />But even putting this aside, one more impediment afflicts casters that does not melees.  Unlike a melee, casters cannot obtain two weapons and be uber.  A rogue who's dual-wielding Khalsazar and some other uber piercer is set for a long, long time even as he goes up in levels because there's honestly nothing better.  Casters, on the other hand, need about 8-9 spells every two levels or else they'd fall behind.  A melee might obtain 3-4 weapon upgrades from 60-65 depending on guild and be uber.  A caster needs more than a dozen spells.  Tell a rogue that he must obtain a dozen daggers in order to be balanced and see what he says.  <br /><br />One argument to this is that spells drop more often than melee weapons.  True, but there are also more classes needing them.  There are only three pure melee classes in EQ: warrior, rogue, and monk.  The rest need parchments.  There's a big competition here that melees don't even have to worry about.  And they get more loot in general (since melee loot is usually more common than caster loot).  Therein lies another imbalance.<br /><br />VI is seriously underestimating the amount of competition for parchments, IMO.  If it's just casters - fine, the drop rates are probably alright, and the spells'll come down to you eventually and probably relatively fast since casters are only four classes out of EQ's 14.  But this ain't true.  Eleven classes require parchments in order to increase in power.  Elven freaking classes.  That's ~80% EQ's population.  And parchments drop how often? This is worse than FP.  With FP, the spell was rare, but when it did drop only one class out of 14 wanted it.  With about 20-30 level 60+ necros per server, that's not alot of demand for a spell that has a chance of dropping off of half a dozen mobs that are almost always killed.  Compare that to runes/spec parchments.<br /><br />VI needs to seriously reevaluate their priorities.  Four items dropping off a boss that also drop four parchments is BS.  Parchments != loot.  You need 3-4 times the amount of parchments as melee loot to begin with, and then multiply that again by how many freaking spells per caster level and the chance of repeats, and you get my meaning.  A boss should be dropping a dozen parchments per kill if he dropped 4 items as loot.  A 2-item dropping boss should drop 6-7 parchments.  I should get half a dozen spectral parchments in the time it takes me to get one Wingblade.  After all, what's a wingblade but a weapon for maybe 5 classes in EQ? Compare that to something for 11 classes in EQ that every class of those 11 also need multiple copies of.  Something's really screwed up here.<br /><br />Anyways, this is my rant.<br /><br /><br /><br />Etadanik the Redeemed</span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
                    </tr>
